To kick off this Abonnement exercise, the reader must explore the dataset. Therefore, we will take a quick peak at what it contains. There are 60 observations with four variables. Those variables include ‘decision,’ ‘temps.lect,’ ‘temps.tele,’ and ‘nbre.revues.’ The only variable that is not an integer is ‘temps.tele’ which is numeric. Within the missing values analysis, it is noticed there are no NAs present. Last but not least, the summary table shows the breakout for each variable. It is important to note that ‘decision’ is binary and therefore, it only has values 0 or 1 which aligns to the data details given for this assignment.

To look closer at the relationship between two variables, please see the correlation matrix below.

cormat <- round(cor(Abonnements),2) # Round the correlation coefficient to two decimal places

melted_cormat <- melt(cormat) # One way to reshape and elongate the data frame

# Get upper triangle of the correlation matrix
  get_upper_tri <- function(cormat){ 
    cormat[lower.tri(cormat)]<- NA
    return(cormat)
  }

# Rename the correlation coefficient value
upper_tri <- get_upper_tri(cormat)
upper_tri
##             decision temps.lect temps.tele nbre.revues
## decision           1       0.49      -0.53       -0.10
## temps.lect        NA       1.00      -0.72        0.08
## temps.tele        NA         NA       1.00       -0.02
## nbre.revues       NA         NA         NA        1.00
# Use correlation between variables as distance
reorder_cormat <- function(cormat){ 
dd <- as.dist((1-cormat)/2)
hc <- hclust(dd)
cormat <-cormat[hc$order, hc$order]
}

# Reorder the correlation matrix
cormat <- reorder_cormat(cormat)
upper_tri <- get_upper_tri(cormat)

# Melt the correlation matrix
melted_cormat <- melt(upper_tri, na.rm = TRUE)

# Create a ggheatmap with multiple characteristics 
ggheatmap <- ggplot(melted_cormat, aes(Var2, Var1, fill = value)) +
  geom_tile(color = "white") +
  scale_fill_gradient2(low = "purple", high = "blue", mid = "white", midpoint = 0, limit = c(-1,1), space = "Lab", name="Pearson\nCorrelation") +
  ggtitle("Correlation Heatmap") + # Title name
  theme_minimal() + # Minimal theme, keeps in the lines
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 1, size = 12, hjust = 1)) +
  coord_fixed() +
  geom_text(aes(Var2, Var1, label = value), color = "black", size = 2)

# Print the heat map
print(ggheatmap)

To give a better representation of the data, we can review the Heatmap. It can be seen that there is a higher negative relationship between ‘temps.lect’ and ‘temps.tele’ at -0.72. Additionally, it is fascinating to see that when comparing ‘decision’ to other variables, it has a positive relationship with ‘temps.lect’ but not with ‘temps.tele.’

2 Classical Logistic Regression

2.1 | 2.2 Parameter Estimation, Deviance Analysis, Goodness-of-Fit, and Residual Analysis

# Run the glm as it performs the estimation for a classical logistic regression
Abonnements.glm = glm(decision ~ ., family = binomial(link = "logit"), data = Abonnements)

# Review the logistics summary output
summary(Abonnements.glm)

Within the logistic model, there are two variables (‘temps.tele’ and ‘nbre.revues’) that are not statistically significant since there p-values are higher than alpha = 0.05. When interpreting the coefficients, we can review the only variable that is significant, ‘temps.lect.’ A one unit increase in this predictor variable is associated with an average change of 0.07124 in the log odds of the response variable am taking on a value of 1. Before moving forward with the analysis though, it is critical to check the residuals to see if there are any patterns that an analyst would not approve.

Additional Information:

  • The null deviance in the output tells us how well the response variable can be predicted by a model with only an intercept term.

  • The residual deviance tells us how well the response variable can be predicted by the specific model that we fit with p predictor variables. The lower the value, the better the model is able to predict the value of the response variable.

  • The Akaike information criterion (AIC) is a metric that is used to compare the fit of different regression models. The lower the value, the better the regression model is able to fit the data.

Resource: https://www.statology.org/interpret-glm-output-in-r/

# Plot the residuals
PlotResidLogist(Abonnements.glm)

Residuals can be defined in several ways. The first is through the deviance residuals which is the contribution of each observation to the total. The second one is the Pearson residuals which is a measure of adequacy of the model. According to slide 532, a residual will be considered large if its absolute value exceeds (approximately) 2. Therefore, we can see that there is a problem within both of these charts. To the left, points 18 and 25 exceed 2. The same issue is seen in the Pearson analysis. For the moment, we can try to remove these two observations and look at the model again.

# Outlier removal
Abonnements_outlier = Abonnements[-c(18,25),] 

# Run the glm as it performs the estimation for a classical logistic regression
Abonnements.glm2 = glm(decision ~ ., family = binomial(link = "logit"), data = Abonnements_outlier)

# Review the logistics summary output
summary(Abonnements.glm2)

By removing points 18 and 25, there are now two variables that are statistically significant, ‘temps.lect’ and ‘temps.tele’ since their p-values do not exceed 0.05. We will review the residuals once again to see if any points exceed the 2 threshold.

# Plot the residuals
PlotResidLogist(Abonnements.glm2)

If you recall from the previous residual analysis, point 5 was very close to exceeding 2. After removing the last two points, 5 now meets that criteria to possibly be removed. Since it was not over the threshold before, we will not delete it. As in TPs 5 and 6, we must check that these residuals are assuming:
1. There should be a similar variability about the X-axis at all points, around 0 on the Y -axis
2. Check the relationship or patterns
3. Check the normality of the errors

It would appear that there are no issues!

The anova() function is helpful to see how the model progresses as more variables are added. For instance, there are four ‘levels’ within the output above since the dataset has that many variables. In each row, it shows important metrics such as deviance, degrees of freedom, and p-value. If we break out each row, it would contain these variables:

  • Row 1 (NULL): Model only includes the intercept (no p-value)
  • Row 2: (‘temps.lect’): Model includes the intercept and ‘temps.lect’ (p-value < 0.05)
  • Row 3: (‘temps.tele’): Model includes the intercept, ‘temps.lect,’ and ‘temps.tele’ (p-value < 0.05)
  • Row 4: (‘nbre.revues’): Model includes the intercept, ‘temps.lect,’ ‘temps.tele’ and ‘nbre.revues’ (p-value > 0.05)

‘nbre.revues’ continues to not be significant. Additionally, the deviance represents the (log)-likelihood of the ‘saturated model’ with the likelihood of the ‘applied’ model under Ho. It can be seen that between the third and fourth row that those variables are very close (0.0009). This could potentially mean that one of those could be removed. It is likely to be ‘nbre.revues’ since its p-value exceeds 0.05.

To choose the best model, we removed the two outliers and ‘nbre.revues’ to see how well these assumptions would work compared of we kept everything the same like the first glm model. The goal is to rerun the classical logistic regression to hopefully get the best fitting model!

# Run the glm as it performs the estimation for a classical logistic regression
Abonnements.glm3 = glm(decision ~ temps.lect + temps.tele, family = binomial(link = "logit"), data = Abonnements_outlier)

# Review the logistics summary output
summary(Abonnements.glm3)

If the reader reviews the output of the logistic model, the anova table, and residual analyzes, there are improvements that can be seen within the data. For one, both variables are significant (p-value > 0.05) while the prior model only had one. Secondly, the deviance between all four variables and only three is similar as they are close to zero (0.0009 to -0.00092888) with a high p-value. The residuals appear as they were before with the outlier at 5. Therefore, we can conclude that we would continue to keep ‘nbre.revues’ out of our model.

# Goodness-of-fit results
HosLem.test(Abonnements_outlier$decision, fitted(Abonnements.glm3))
## 
##  Hosmer-Lemeshow goodness of fit test
## 
## data:  Abonnements_outlier$decision, fitted(Abonnements.glm3)
## X-squared = 8.7276, df = 8, p-value = 0.3658

The last part of the classical logistic regression is to check the goodness-of-fit. Since the p-value is above alpha (0.05), this indicates that there is no evidence of the model being of poor fit. The model that only includes ‘temps.lect’ and ‘temps.tele’ is the best and most simplistic for this dataset.

3 Robust Logistic Regression

3.1 Parameter estimation and goodness of fit

# Run the glmRob as it performs the estimation for a robust logistic regression
Abonnements.glmRob = glmrob(decision ~ temps.lect + temps.tele, family = binomial(link = "logit"), data = Abonnements)

# Review the logistics summary output
summary(Abonnements.glmRob)

# Plot the residuals
PlotResidLogistRob(Abonnements.glmRob)

Since the classical approach included looking at the best variables to include in the model, that exercise will not be repeated. Therefore, we can focus on ‘temps.lect’ and ‘temps.tele’ within the robust model. Out of the 60 observations, there are 7 weighted differently than 1. Those seven points account for 11.67% of the data which is a low enough value to not consider unacceptable. Since there are additional outliers that are weighted differently, we want to ensure that the residuals follow the three assumptions from earlier. They appear to be around zero, there are no patterns/structures, and as many points are positive as there are negative. We are in the clear!

# Goodness-of-fit results
HosLem.test(Abonnements$decision, fitted(Abonnements.glmRob))
## 
##  Hosmer-Lemeshow goodness of fit test
## 
## data:  Abonnements$decision, fitted(Abonnements.glmRob)
## X-squared = 86.32, df = 8, p-value = 2.554e-15

Checking the goodness-of-fit one last time. It shows that there is no significance difference between the observed data and the model since the p-value is below 0.05.

Conclusion

I would inform the commercial director that the most influential factors are ‘temps.lect’ and ‘temps.tele.’ To calculate the impact of both of these variables, review the latest summary for the robust model. The robust model will be the best method due to the numerous extreme values that are observed. After reviewing the coefficients…

  • When a customer spends more time reading a magazine, the odds of continuing the subscription increases by a factor of exp(0.13783) = 1.148 if all other constants are fixed. Since the value is greater than 1, it denotes that it has a positive impact on decision.

  • When a customer spends more time watching the television, the odds of continuing the subscription decreases by a factor of exp(0.06033) = 0.941 if all other constants are fixed. Since the value is less than 1, it denotes that it has a negative impact on decision.

Good luck to the director!

cormat <- round(cor(Ronflement),2) # Round the correlation coefficient to two decimal places

melted_cormat <- melt(cormat) # One way to reshape and elongate the data frame

# Get upper triangle of the correlation matrix
  get_upper_tri <- function(cormat){ 
    cormat[lower.tri(cormat)]<- NA
    return(cormat)
  }

# Rename the correlation coefficient value
upper_tri <- get_upper_tri(cormat)

# Use correlation between variables as distance
reorder_cormat <- function(cormat){ 
dd <- as.dist((1-cormat)/2)
hc <- hclust(dd)
cormat <-cormat[hc$order, hc$order]
}

# Reorder the correlation matrix
cormat <- reorder_cormat(cormat)
upper_tri <- get_upper_tri(cormat)

# Melt the correlation matrix
melted_cormat <- melt(upper_tri, na.rm = TRUE)

# Create a ggheatmap with multiple characteristics

  scale_fill_gradient2(low = "purple", high = "blue", mid = "white", midpoint = 0, limit = c(-1,1), space = "Lab", name="Pearson\nCorrelation") +
  ggtitle("Correlation Heatmap") + # Title name
  theme_minimal() + # Minimal theme, keeps in the lines
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 1, size = 12, hjust = 1)) +
  coord_fixed() +
  geom_text(aes(Var2, Var1, label = value), color = "black", size = 2)

Within the logistic model, there are three variables (‘age’ ‘alcool,’ and ‘tabac’) that are statistically significant since there p-values are less than alpha = 0.05. When interpreting the coefficients, we can say that one unit increase in this predictor variable is associated with an average change of 0.062702 (‘age’) in the log odds of the response variable am taking on a value of 1. Before moving forward with the analysis though, it is critical to check the residuals to see if there are any patterns that an analyst would want to avoid.

# Plot the residuals
PlotResidLogist(Ronflement.glm)

Residuals can be defined in several ways. The first is through the deviance residuals which is the contribution of each observation to the total. The second one is the Pearson residuals which is a measure of adequacy of the model. According to slide 532, a residual will be considered large if its absolute value exceeds (approximately) 2. Therefore, we can see that there is a problem within both of these charts. To the left, point 21 exceeds 2. The same issue is seen in the Pearson analysis. For the moment, we can try to remove this observation and look at the model again.

Since the classical approach included looking at the best variables to include in the model, that exercise will not be repeated. Therefore, we can focus only on the four variables we kept. Out of the 100 observations, there are 12 that we weighted differently than 1. Those twelve points account for 12.00% of the data which is a low enough value to not consider unacceptable. Since there are additional outliers that are weighted differently, we want to ensure that the residuals follow the three assumptions from earlier. Checking the goodness-of-fit one last time. It shows that there is no significance difference between the observed data and the model since the p-value is below 0.05.

Conclusion

There are several characteristics that have been determined of a typical snorer. Based on the classical logistic regression model:

  • When a customer becomes older, the odds of snoring increases by a factor of exp(0.06828) = 1.071 if all other constants are fixed. Since the value is greater than 1, it denotes that it has a positive impact on decision.

  • When a customer becomes drinks more glasses per day, the odds of snoring increases by a factor of exp(0.25703) = 1.293 if all other constants are fixed. Since the value is greater than 1, it denotes that it has a positive impact on decision.

  • When a customer is a woman, the odds of snoring decreases by a factor of exp(0.99308) = 0.370 if all other constants are fixed. Since the value is less than 1, it denotes that it has a negative impact on decision.

  • When a customer is a smoker, the odds of snoring decreases by a factor of exp(1.44139) = 0.237 if all other constants are fixed. Since the value is less than 1, it denotes that it has a negative impact on decision.

Overall, the characteristics of a possible snorer would be an older male who drinks alcohol and smokes.
